Quarter the @chestnut mushrooms{1}. Peel and grate the @ginger{1} and @garlic clove{1}.

Heat a #saucepan{} over medium heat and add a glug of @oil{}. When the oil is hot, pop in your chestnut mushrooms and cook for ~{5%minutes} until nicely browned. Add your ginger, garlic and @red thai style paste{1} to the pan and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Pour in the @water{1/2} and bring to the boil.

When it comes to the boil, turn the heat to low and cook for ~{10%minutes}. This is the base of your broth! As it simmers away, finish off the rest of your prep. Remove the bottoms from the @enoki mushrooms{1}, pull them apart to separate them and keep to one side. Separate the stalks from the leaves of the @coriander{1} and finely chop them both. Add your coriander stalks to your broth and keep your leaves until later.

Remove the roots from the @spring onions{3} and slice widthways as thinly as you can. Pour the @soy sauce{1.5} and @rice vinegar{1} into a #bowl{} and mix in your spring onion. Keep to one side.

Once your broth has been simmering for 10 mins, pop the @udon noodles{200} in and cook on low heat for a further ~{1%minute} to make sure they are hot.

In the meantime, heat a #frying pan{} over medium-low heat and add the @sesame seeds{1}. Cook for ~{2%minutes} without oil, stirring every now and then to make sure they colour evenly. Remove them from the pan when they are golden brown.

Take your broth off the heat and get ready to serve! Pop a handful of raw @baby spinach{1/2} leaves into the bottom of each #bowl{} and ladle your hot broth into the bowls. Make sure you evenly share out your noodles and chestnut mushrooms! Top with your raw enoki mushrooms and sprinkle over your coriander leaves.

Finish your broth by spooning over your soy sauce, rice vinegar, spring onion mix and your toasted sesame seeds.

> Broth is super trendy at the moment and mushrooms will never go out of fashion - so André has added some udon noodles to the mix to make this a HelloFresh special. MMMmm!